---
title: "From Python to Lateralus"
author: bad-antics
date: 2026-04-06
abstract: As a seasoned Python developer, you're likely no stranger to functional programming and first-class functions. But if you're looking to bring your skills to the lateralus language, there's more than meets the eye.
---

## Familiar Ground

Lateralus is built on top of the concepts we've grown accustomed to in Python. If you're already comfortable with loops and control structures, you'll find that the syntax translates relatively smoothly. However, be prepared for some unexpected twists.

### Loops

In lateralus, `for` loops are functionally identical to their Python counterparts:
fn example(x: int) {
    for i in [1, 2, 3] {
        print(i * x)
    }
}
However, keep in mind that lateralus encourages a more declarative style. You may find yourself using `when` statements instead:
fn example(x: int) {
    let result = when(x > 0) { i: i * i } else { i: 0 }
    print(result)
}

## Functions

Functions in lateralus are also very similar to those in Python. The main difference lies in how they handle side effects. Lateralus uses the `->` operator to specify return types, making it easier to write pure functions:
fn add(a: int, b: int) -> int {
    return a + b
}

// This is equivalent to:
fn add(a: int, b: int) {
    return a + b
}
## Pipelines

One of the most significant changes from Python is the way you'll work with data in lateralus. Pipelines allow you to compose functions together to achieve complex operations. Think of them as a series of function calls on steroids:
fn parse_json(data: str) -> JSON {
    ...
}

fn format_json(json: JSON) -> str {
    ...
}

let json_data = "{'key': 'value'}"
let formatted_data = format_json(parse_json(json_data))
print(formatted_data)
This may seem daunting at first, but trust us – once you get the hang of it, pipelines will become your new favorite thing.

